The Vieques, Puerto Rico, Naval Training Range, a site that practically screams "environmental disaster waiting to happen," was a [United States naval facility](/United_States_Navy) perched rather uncomfortably on the island of [Vieques](/Vieques). This island, a mere 5 miles east of the considerably larger and presumably less irradiated mainland [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico), found itself in the Navy's crosshairs for military exercises starting way back in November 1941. The bombs eventually stopped falling in 2001, and the Navy, with its characteristic grace and efficiency, finally packed up and vacated the premises in 2003.

### Searching for a Location

One would think the Navy, in its quest for a suitable training ground, might have considered the long-term implications. Apparently, that was a bit too much to ask. The acquisition of land between 1941 and 1950 was a rather haphazard affair. Wealthy landowners, bless their hearts, were compensated with land sold at a "fair price" – a fixed price, naturally. The smaller native landowners and tenant farmers, however, weren't so lucky. Some were compensated for their land, others merely relocated to less desirable parts of the island, and some were simply, and quite unceremoniously, forced out. The land grab amounted to 22,000 acres, a staggering two-thirds of the island. Of this, a substantial 8,000 acres on the western end was designated as a naval ammunition depot. This particular parcel was eventually returned to the Municipality of Vieques on May 1, 2001, though I suspect it came with a rather hefty "as-is" disclaimer.

The eastern end of the island, however, was where the real fun happened. Live training exercises, ship-to-shore gunfire that probably made the local wildlife question their life choices, air-to-ground bombing runs that likely resembled a fireworks display gone terribly wrong, and US Marine amphibious landings – all standard Navy fare, starting from the 1940s. Nestled within this operational playground was a 900-acre Live Impact Area (LIA), specifically designed for the full-on, no-holds-barred use of live ordnance. Conveniently, this LIA was situated at the easternmost tip of the island, ensuring it was as far away as possible from the civilian population. Out of sight, out of mind, I suppose, until the environmental cleanup bills started rolling in.

### Description of the Navy's Facilities

The former Vieques Naval Training Range (VNTR), a name that now evokes more dread than patriotism, occupied the eastern half of the island. Adjacent to it, on the western one-third, was the former Naval Ammunition Support Detachment (NASD). Sandwiched between these two veritable toxic playgrounds were the unassuming local civilian communities of [Isabel Segunda](/Isabel_Segunda,_Puerto_Rico) and [Esperanza](/Esperanza,_Puerto_Rico). One can only imagine the constant, low-grade hum of anxiety that must have permeated these towns, a soundtrack to the relentless military operations.

### Operations on East Vieques

The VNTR, sprawling across approximately 14,573 acres, was the stage for ground warfare and amphibious training for the Marines, as well as naval gunfire support and air-to-ground training. It was meticulously (or perhaps haphazardly) divided into four distinct operational zones, stretching from west to east: the Eastern Maneuver Area (EMA), the Surface Impact Area (SIA), the Live Impact Area (LIA), and finally, the Eastern Conservation Area (ECA) clinging to the easternmost tip of the island. This ECA, a supposed sanctuary, was still part of the military's domain, which, given the circumstances, probably meant it was conserving something other than nature.

### Operations on West Vieques

The western side of the island, a hub for storing and processing supplies and, more importantly, disposing of waste, presented its own unique set of environmental challenges. The sites slated for the arduous task of environmental cleanup were a veritable rogues' gallery of industrial negligence:

*   **Laguna Arenas:** A former general [waste dump](/Waste_dump) situated unceremoniously within a [mangrove swamp](/Mangrove_swamp) along Highway 200. Because nothing says "environmental responsibility" like burying your trash in a delicate ecosystem.
*   **Underground Storage Tank:** In 1970, an underground storage tank, presumably filled with something noxious like waste oil, was buried in the former public works area. It was only removed in 1996. Better late than never, I suppose, though the "better" is highly debatable.
*   **Asphalt Plant:** A former [asphalt plant](/Asphalt_plant) operated on the south side of Route 200 from the 1960s until 1998. One can only speculate about the cocktail of chemicals that seeped into the ground during its decades of operation.

Further investigations, conducted as part of an environmental baseline survey, unearthed a munitions open-burn/open-detonation area on the western tip of the island, near Punta Boca Quebrada. This discovery led to the identification of 16 potential open-burn/open-detonation sites in the vicinity. Consequently, 24 acres of roads and beaches underwent inspection and clearance for munitions, with the cleanup efforts wrapping up in December 2011. It’s a small victory, I suppose, that they managed to clear some of the physical debris, but the invisible contamination likely lingers.

### Base Closure and Cleanup

Following the base's closure, the Governor of [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico), [Sila Calderon](/Sila_Calderon), astutely requested that [Vieques](/Vieques) be added to the U.S. [National Priorities List](/National_Priorities_List) as a designated [superfund](/Superfund) cleanup site. As of 2014, the EPA had identified a rather alarming list of contaminants and ordnances plaguing the western portion of the naval station. This included unexploded ordnance [UXO](/UXO), remnants of exploded ordnance, and a veritable chemical soup of [mercury](/Mercury_(element)), [lead](/Lead), [copper](/Copper), [magnesium](/Magnesium), [lithium](/Lithium), [napalm](/Napalm), and [depleted uranium](/Depleted_uranium), alongside other unspecified nasties. The eastern portion of the site, with its own unique brand of contamination, was suspected to harbor [polychlorinated biphenyls](/Polychlorinated_biphenyl) (PCB), [solvents](/Solvents), and [pesticides](/Pesticides). A truly delightful inheritance.

Both the [US Navy](/US_Navy) and the EPA have been engaged in a rather protracted dance of coordinating cleanup efforts.

*   **Munitions Response Program:** The Navy recently concluded an expanded range assessment at the former Vieques Naval Training Range (VNTR). They are also undertaking a time-critical removal action (TCRA) for munitions and explosives of concern (MEC) on the surface at the former Live Impact Area (LIA) and Eastern Conservation Area (ECA). Additionally, Non-Time Critical Removal Actions (NTCRA) are in progress for surface MEC at the Surface Impact Area (SIA) and for subsurface MEC along selected roads and beaches within the former VNTR. It sounds like a lot of acronyms for a very slow and complicated process.

*   **Environmental Restoration Program:** On the western side, at the Former Naval Ammunition Support Detachment, the Navy conducted a Remedial Investigation/Feasibility Study (RI/FS) at seven sites. Four NTCRA's were completed for the removal of solid waste piles and debris in FY09. A Record of Decision (ROD) was issued in September 2008 for one operable unit, AOC H, and subsequent RODs for AOC J, R and SWMU-7 (NASD) and SWMU-1 (VNTR) were signed in 2011.

Across the former VNTR, a staggering thirty-six operable units have been investigated. Decisions have been made for "No action" at ten sites – a decision I find particularly concerning. Site Inspection/Expanded Site Inspection (SI/ESI) for another 26 operable units was completed in FY09. Seventeen NTCRA's, six RI/FS, three SI/ESI, and one EE/CA are currently in various stages of progress. It's a monumental task, and one that highlights the sheer scale of the contamination left behind.

As of 2007, the Navy was obligated to "conduct an environmental investigation of its previously owned property under the federal [Resource Conservation and Recovery Act](/Resource_Conservation_and_Recovery_Act) (RCRA) to determine what cleanup actions" were necessary. The EPA, bless their bureaucratic hearts, provided "technical assistance and guidance to the Navy on environmental issues related to the land transfer in western Vieques." The initial assessment was grim: the dense jungle growth, while a testament to nature's resilience, was a significant impediment to testing for contaminants. And attempting to clear this growth was like walking through a minefield, albeit a minefield littered with unexploded ordnance.

For the remainder of Fiscal Year 2015, Congress saw fit to appropriate $17 million for the cleanup of Vieques and a comparatively paltry $1.4 million for [Culebra](/Culebra,_Puerto_Rico). By 2014, the Navy had already shelled out approximately $220 million since 2003, all in the name of investigating and cleaning up [contaminated land](/Contaminated_land) on Vieques. Since 2007, a rather optimistic half of the budgeted funds for munitions removal had been directed towards 23 local companies in Puerto Rico. The stark reality, as of 2014, was that the Navy was spending more money annually on cleaning up Vieques than on any other former Navy installation in the U.S. And the cleanup efforts? They are projected to drag on until 2032. That's a rather long time to live with the consequences of military ambition.

### Protests Against U.S. Navy 1999

The year 1999 marked a turning point, a crescendo of discontent against the Navy's decades-long occupation and use of Vieques for bombing practice. The catalyst was the tragic death of [David Sanes](/David_Sanes), a civilian security guard, who was killed by a stray bomb during a routine exercise. This incident ignited a firestorm of protest, drawing in Vieques residents and activists from across Puerto Rico, including figures like [Ruben Berrios](/Ruben_Berrios) and [Tito Kayak](/Tito_Kayak). Their activism escalated, often involving the direct occupation of live-fire areas within the military reservation. The cause gained significant traction, attracting the attention of prominent figures such as [Jesse Jackson](/Jesse_Jackson), [Robert Kennedy Jr.](/Robert_Kennedy_Jr.), [Al Sharpton](/Al_Sharpton), and a host of U.S. Representatives and Senators, including [Luis Gutiérrez](/Luis_Guti%C3%A9rrez) and [Nydia Velázquez](/Nydia_Vel%C3%A1zquez). Even Nobel laureate [Rigoberta Menchú](/Rigoberta_Mench%C3%BA) and actor [Edward James Olmos](/Edward_James_Olmos) lent their voices and presence, with Olmos famously being jailed for trespassing on federal property.

In response to the mounting pressure, President [Clinton](/Bill_Clinton) directed Secretary of Defense [William Cohen](/William_Cohen) to assemble a special panel to investigate the situation. Chaired by Frank Rush, the then-acting Assistant Secretary of Defense for force management policy, this panel, often referred to as the Rush panel, meticulously documented the history and legal complexities of the issue. Their comprehensive report, complete with 11 recommendations, was released on October 19, 1999.

A significant step toward resolution came in January 2000 when President Clinton and Governor of Puerto Rico, [Pedro Rosselló](/Pedro_Rossell%C3%B3), jointly called for a referendum on Vieques. Initially scheduled for November 2001 and later rescheduled for January 2002, this referendum offered voters a stark choice: either end the military's use of the range by May 2003 or allow military operations to continue indefinitely.

However, the path to peace was not linear. On April 27, 2001, the Navy controversially resumed operations, reigniting the protests. Then, on June 14, 2001, the [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush) administration issued a decisive order: military training operations on Vieques would cease by May 2003. This decision effectively superseded any prior agreements or plans made under the Clinton administration, signaling a clear shift in federal policy.

Fort Bundy, a facility that straddled the [Roosevelt Roads Naval Station](/Roosevelt_Roads_Naval_Station) and parts of Vieques, also found itself entangled in the protests. President [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush), in his capacity as Commander-in-Chief, granted Puerto Rico the rights to manage the former military installations on Vieques, including Fort Bundy. As a direct consequence of this decision, the Roosevelt Roads Naval Station was reclassified as NAPR (Naval Activity Puerto Rico). While still under the purview of the DoD Police for security, it remained an active military installation.

The relentless efforts of the protesters ultimately bore fruit. In May 2003, the Atlantic Fleet Weapons Training Facility on Vieques Island was officially closed. This was followed in May 2004 by the closure of the [Roosevelt Roads Naval Station](/Roosevelt_Roads_Naval_Station), the U.S. Navy's last remaining base on mainland Puerto Rico. The closure of Roosevelt Roads represented a significant economic blow to the region, as it had employed approximately 1,000 local contractors and contributed an estimated $300 million annually to the local economy.

### Protester History

**David Sanes**

The tragic incident that galvanized the protests occurred on April 19, 1999. David Sanes Rodríguez, a civilian employee working as a security guard, was killed when military ordnance, dropped during a training mission, landed perilously close to his post. According to a Congressional research report, an F-18 Marine Corps aircraft released two 500-pound bombs that struck the security post, resulting in Rodriguez's death and injuring four others. The report clarified that the ordnance was released "within the overall range perimeter." Following this fatal accident, the training range was temporarily suspended.

The death of Rodriguez served as a stark reminder of the risks involved and ignited a wave of outrage among the local populace. President Clinton, a promise later echoed by his successor George W. Bush, pledged that the Navy would withdraw from Vieques by May 2003, offering a glimmer of hope to the beleaguered island.

**Encampments**

In the months following Sanes's demise, small wooden structures began to appear within the confines of the practice grounds, transforming them into makeshift encampments. These sites quickly became focal points for protesters from across the island-municipality, drawing considerable attention.

The protests, initially a local affair, soon garnered international recognition. Activists and sympathizers from around the globe joined the cause, adding their voices to the chorus demanding the Navy's departure. A diverse array of prominent figures offered their support, including political leader [Ruben Berrios](/Ruben_Berrios), musicians [Danny Rivera](/Danny_Rivera), [Robi Draco Rosa](/Draco_Rosa), and [Ricky Martin](/Ricky_Martin), boxing champion [Félix "Tito" Trinidad](/F%C3%A9lix_Trinidad), acclaimed writers [Ana Lydia Vega](/Ana_Lydia_Vega) and [Giannina Braschi](/Giannina_Braschi), American actor [Edward James Olmos](/Edward_James_Olmos), and Nobel Peace Prize laureate [Rigoberta Menchú](/Rigoberta_Mench%C3%BA). The support extended to influential American figures like [Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.](/Robert_F._Kennedy,_Jr.), [Al Sharpton](/Al_Sharpton), and [Rev. Jesse Jackson](/Rev._Jesse_Jackson). Even [Pope John Paul II](/Pope_John_Paul_II) expressed a desire for peace on Vieques. The [Archbishop of San Juan](/Archbishop_of_San_Juan), [Roberto González Nieves](/Roberto_Gonz%C3%A1lez_Nieves), played a pivotal role, orchestrating a coalition of Puerto Rican church leaders that captured international attention. Notably, Olmos, Sharpton, and Kennedy all faced imprisonment for their activism. During Kennedy's incarceration in Puerto Rico, his wife gave birth to their sixth child, whom they named Aidan Caohman Vieques Kennedy, a poignant tribute to the island's struggle.

The [Movimiento Socialista de Trabajadores](/Movimiento_Socialista_de_Trabajadores) also engaged in a series of direct actions, successfully infiltrating the bombing ranges to disrupt bombing operations without being apprehended.

**Massive Occupation of Practice Range**

On May 4, 2000, a significant turning point occurred when civil disobedience encampments situated within the practice grounds were forcibly evacuated by a combined force of [U.S. Marshals](/United_States_Marshals_Service), [Marines](/United_States_Marine_Corps), and [Navy](/United_States_Navy) personnel.

Just five days later, in an event that captivated global attention, hundreds of protesters and supporters, representing a diverse spectrum of ideologies and hailing from all corners of the world, breached the military practice grounds. Among them were natives of Vieques, numerous Puerto Ricans, Hollywood celebrities, religious figures including priests, pastors, and friars, athletes, and politicians, including U.S. Representatives [Luis Gutiérrez](/Luis_Guti%C3%A9rrez) and [Nydia Velázquez](/Nydia_Vel%C3%A1zquez). This incursion, which had been widely publicized, resulted in the arrest of the protesters by Marshals. Both sides of the conflict, perhaps surprisingly, seemed keen to avoid direct confrontation with the military.

Adhering to a strict policy of non-violence, the protesters maintained a peaceful demeanor throughout their arrests, their chants of "Paz para Vieques" ("Peace for Vieques") echoing through the air. Others offered prayers or sang songs of peace and faith. While a few required physical removal, they offered no resistance or insults. Many were released within hours of their detention, while others were freed a few days later. Only a select few received sentences ranging from one to six months, primarily for the charge of [trespassing](/Trespassing) on U.S. military territory.

Incursions continued, and protests eventually came to an end. As U.S. Navy bombing practices persisted, the incursions into the practice grounds continued unabated. However, the tide began to turn when the U.S. government formally announced that the military would indeed be withdrawing from the island by May 2003.

On March 31, 2004, the United States officially closed its [Roosevelt Roads Naval Station](/Roosevelt_Roads_Naval_Station) on mainland Puerto Rico. A skeleton crew of 200 personnel, a significant reduction from the approximately 1,200 civilian and 700 military staff, remained on-site to oversee the final transfer of the property. The closure of the Roosevelt Roads base resulted in a considerable economic downturn for Puerto Rico, with the Navy estimating an annual loss of $250 to $300 million. Admiral [Robert J. Natter](/Robert_J._Natter), commander of the Atlantic Fleet, was quoted as stating, "Without Vieques there is no way I need the Navy facilities at Roosevelt Roads — none. It's a drain on Defense Department and taxpayer dollars."

Despite the economic repercussions, the government of Puerto Rico announced plans to reopen the base's airport, envisioning it as a major Caribbean air cargo hub. This initiative aimed to alleviate congestion at [Luis Muñoz Marín International Airport](/Luis_Mu%C3%B1oz_Mar%C3%ADn_International_Airport) and extend its operational lifespan indefinitely, without the need for further expansion. Additionally, the airport was intended to centralize general aviation activities currently scattered across various municipal airports, thereby generating substantial cost savings for the [Puerto Rico Ports Authority](/Puerto_Rico_Ports_Authority) in terms of maintenance and operational expenses. Other strategic plans were in motion to leverage different sections of the former base for the benefit of the local economy. A significant portion of the undeveloped land was designated for ecological preservation, a small consolation in the wake of extensive environmental damage.

### Further Protests

On April 30, 2003, a large contingent of supporters of the Cause of Vieques converged on the island-municipality to hold a celebratory event within the former bombing practice grounds. The proceedings were broadcast live on national television news. The following day, May 1, 2003, the crowd entered the former bombing range en masse. However, the celebratory atmosphere took a sharp and aggressive turn, a stark contrast to the peaceful protests previously orchestrated by some within the group.

The [Police](/Police) [Task force](/Task_force) of Puerto Rico, alongside the Vieques Police and other law enforcement officials, were mobilized from the main island. These forces, however, appeared unprepared for the eruption of violence that accompanied the celebration. The president of the [Teachers Federation of Puerto Rico](/Teachers_Federation_of_Puerto_Rico), a prominent leader in the cause, was captured on television cameras engaging in acts of vandalism and destruction. The crowd proceeded to demolish a former Navy guardhouse and military trucks using drop hammers. The television footage subsequently served as crucial evidence for the criminal indictment of the perpetrators, as the destroyed property was now under the ownership of the [NRCS](/Natural_Resources_Conservation_Service).

The indicted individuals contended that their actions were a direct result of the accumulated resentment and bitterness stemming from decades of suffering caused by the Navy's relentless bombing practices on the island. [Norma Burgos](/Norma_Burgos), a Senator of Puerto Rico who had herself been imprisoned for trespassing on the bombing range months earlier, sought to justify the destructive behavior by drawing a parallel to the fall of [Saddam Hussein](/Saddam_Hussein)'s statue during the recent [invasion of Iraq](/2003_invasion_of_Iraq). She argued that U.S. soldiers had utilized an Army tank, a piece of U.S. government property, to achieve this objective. Despite their defense, their arguments failed to sway the court, and more than a dozen of those charged were ultimately imprisoned for "damages and destruction of public property."

### Military Withdrawal 2001-2003

In 2001, the United States Navy officially withdrew from western Vieques, an area that had served as a critical ammunition depot. Subsequently, the [United States Fish and Wildlife Service](/United_States_Fish_and_Wildlife_Service) assumed control of approximately 3,100 acres (13 km²) of this land, representing about half of the formerly occupied military property. During the Navy's tenure, an estimated 22 million pounds (10,000 tonnes) of military and industrial waste, including oils, solvents, lubricants, lead paint, acid, and countless 55-gallon drums, were unceremoniously deposited on the western portion of the island. According to McCaffrey, citing data from the Universidad Metropolitana, the extent of leaching from these buried contaminants remains largely unknown. By 2005, the Navy was actively investigating 17 potentially contaminated sites.

On May 1, 2003, the Navy completed the transfer of all its holdings to the [U.S. Department of the Interior](/U.S._Department_of_the_Interior). This included the entirety of the Navy's eastern portion of the island – a vast 14,573 acres (58.97 km²), which had primarily functioned as a dumping ground for ordnance. McCaffrey further cites U.S. Navy data indicating that Vieques was subjected to bombing an average of 180 days per year. In 1998, the final year before protests disrupted maneuvers, the Navy unleashed 23,000 bombs on the island, the majority of which contained explosives.

The live impact range, arguably the most heavily contaminated zone, was granted the highest level of environmental protection: that of a "wilderness preserve." The Fish and Wildlife Service proudly proclaims the [Vieques Wildlife Refuge](/Vieques_Wildlife_Refuge) as an ecologically diverse Caribbean [wildlife refuge](/Wildlife_refuge). However, the EPA has designated this same refuge as a superfund site. The designation of much of this land as wildlife refuges effectively prohibits human access, thereby allowing the Navy to sidestep its cleanup obligations. Whether this strategic designation was a deliberate maneuver to avoid environmental remediation remains a subject of intense debate.

### Contamination and Health Effects

A sobering survey conducted by the [Puerto Rico Health Department](/Puerto_Rico_Department_of_Health) revealed a stark reality: the cancer rate in Vieques was a staggering 27% higher than that of mainland Puerto Rico. In a 2001 federal lawsuit, Vieques' environmental groups and residents boldly accused the Navy of inflicting "more damage than any other single actor in the history of Puerto Rico." The plaintiffs argued that the Navy's extensive activities had thoroughly contaminated much of the island's eastern portion with a wide spectrum of toxic substances. Citing figures from [Franciscans International](/Franciscans_International), and based on Navy data, it is estimated that over six decades, approximately 5 million pounds (2,000 t) of ordnance were dropped on Vieques annually. This ordnance contained a lethal cocktail of toxic compounds and elements, including [arsenic](/Arsenic), [lead](/Lead), [mercury](/Mercury_(element)), [cadmium](/Cadmium), [depleted uranium](/Depleted_uranium), and [napalm](/Napalm), along with tons of a peculiar fiberglass-like substance. The insidious nature of most of these toxins lies in their persistence and their propensity to [bioaccumulate](/Bioaccumulate) within living organisms.

For decades, environmentalists have voiced grave concerns that contaminants originating from naval exercises have infiltrated various parts of the island through the air, water, and soil. The population of Vieques lives directly downwind from the bombing zones, meaning that airborne toxins, such as depleted uranium, could easily come into contact with civilians. Representative [Charles Rangel](/Charles_Rangel) (D-NY), upon investigating the contamination in Vieques, made a critical observation:

> A number of studies conducted by well-qualified scientists from universities in the United States and in Puerto Rico reveal that there is a high probability that the compounds released by the Navy exercises and chemical testing created toxic levels in the environment and could be the cause of serious medical conditions affecting the people of Vieques.

The same newspaper article further reported that a study by the Puerto Rico Health Department had identified elevated levels of [heavy metals](/Heavy_metals) in plants, animals, and humans. These high concentrations of heavy metals appeared to be directly contributing to increased rates of cancer, infant mortality, and childhood [asthma](/Asthma). Within the 980-acre (4.0 km²) live impact range situated at the island's eastern tip, studies have revealed that the groundwater is heavily contaminated with nitrates and explosives. Adding to this grim picture, the floor of the Caribbean Sea is littered with unexploded weapons, ordnance, and sunken barges. Tests conducted in the Icacos Lagoon showed cadmium concentrations in crabs to be an astonishing 1,000 times higher than the [World Health Organization](/World_Health_Organization)'s "tolerable ingestion maximum dosage." Furthermore, toxic levels of heavy metals, including lead, arsenic, selenium, mercury, and zinc, have been detected in numerous species of fish. In the lawsuit filed by environmentalists and the people of Vieques against the Navy, prosecutors highlighted the fact that most Vieques residents rely on these very same species of fish as a primary source of sustenance. Both cadmium and arsenic are known carcinogens. A 1999 study that analyzed hair samples from various age groups of Vieques residents found that a staggering 69% were contaminated with cadmium and arsenic, and a concerning 34% exhibited toxic levels of mercury.

Biologist [Arturo Massol](/Casa_Pueblo) and radiochemist Elba Díaz conducted an unpublished study in 2001 that revealed vegetables and plants growing in the civilian areas of Vieques were heavily contaminated with heavy metals such as lead, cadmium, and copper. Their findings indicated that metal concentrations in edible crops significantly exceeded the maximum levels set by the [European Union](/European_Union) Council and were substantially higher than in plants tested on mainland Puerto Rico. Crops with shallower root systems, such as chilies, pasture grasses, and [squashes](/Squash_(plant)), were found to be more affected than plants with deeper root systems like trees. This observation strongly supports the theory that heavy metals are transported by air to civilian areas via the persistent easterly trade winds that blow directly from the bombing zone.

Mercury, a neurotoxin, poses a severe threat to the brain, cardiovascular system, kidneys, and can be particularly devastating to the developing fetus. According to a 2006 newspaper article, a study by the Puerto Rico Health Department linked abnormally high rates of asthma in children to mercury contamination. In 2004, the infant mortality rate in Vieques was a shocking 55% higher than in the other 77 municipalities in Puerto Rico, registering a rate of nearly 20 per 1,000 live births, compared to the island's average of 12.8.

On November 17, 2002, Milivi Adams, a native of Vieques, succumbed to [cancer](/Cancer). Her death became a potent symbol in the ongoing struggle against the military's presence on the island.

#### Depleted Uranium

In addition to the toxic materials that the Navy had been indiscriminately dropping on Vieques since the 1940s, a new and particularly alarming contaminant entered the picture in 1999: [depleted uranium](/Depleted_uranium) ("DU") bullets. The Navy eventually admitted to firing a mere 263 rounds of these DU bullets. While the [U.S. Department of Defense](/U.S._Department_of_Defense), citing a report by the research corporation [RAND](/RAND), claims that DU poses no threat to human health, Dan Fahey, the Director of Research at the Gulf War Resource Center, points out a critical flaw in this assertion. He argues that the RAND report was woefully incomplete, having deliberately ignored 68 relevant sources that unequivocally demonstrate a clear and dangerous relationship between DU exposure and adverse health effects.

#### Nuclear Target Ship Wreck

In 1958, the veteran World War II Fletcher Class Destroyer [USS Killen](/USS_Killen) (DD593) was repurposed as a target ship for wreckage during the atomic bomb tests conducted as part of [Operation Hardtack I](/Operation_Hardtack_I) at the [Pacific Proving Grounds](/Pacific_Proving_Grounds) (specifically, the WAHOO and UMBRELLA shots). By 1962, it had been towed to [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) for further tests aimed at assessing the structural effects of the ship's exposure to nuclear radiation. The Killen was subsequently struck from the [Naval Vessel Register](/Naval_Vessel_Register) and dispatched to the US Naval Station at [Roosevelt Roads](/Roosevelt_Roads) in January 1963. Its intended purpose was to serve as a target for missile and gunnery practice. It was eventually sunk, or scuttled, in a shallow bay in 1975, and as of 2010, its wreckage still rests on the bay floor. The wreck itself is missing significant portions, including all structures above its main deck, nearly all of the main decking itself, and a section of the ship's stern. A staggering thousands of tons of the ship are unaccounted for.

Studies and site visits conducted in 1999 by a Puerto Rican marine archaeologist and researchers from the [University of Georgia](/University_of_Georgia) discovered nearly two hundred steel barrels of unknown origin and contents amidst the wreckage of the Killen. Drawing upon government descriptions of the nuclear tests conducted in the Pacific, some scientists and environmental activists in Vieques have voiced serious concerns that these barrels may have contained materials used for cleaning up nuclear fallout and were improperly disposed of. This raises the disturbing possibility that these contaminants may have entered the local environment prior to the ship's sinking or subsequently exposed the animals and habitat of Bahia Salina del Sur in Vieques after its submersion.

In 2003, a specialized team from the University of Georgia conducted comprehensive radiological and toxicological tests of the wreckage using advanced underwater detection equipment. The resulting report detailed tests performed on the interiors of the steel barrels at the wreck site, specifically examining four intact barrels and five that were described as 'open.' These were probed with a siphon-extraction tube. The findings indicated that the wreck site did not exhibit elevated radiological signatures in either the ship's hull or the internal components of the barrels. However, the report did raise significant concerns regarding potential contamination from ordnance present at the site. As of 2010, the precise origin and contents of these mysterious barrels remain unknown.

#### Sonic Booms

It has been asserted that the persistent noise generated by the Navy's testing activities has had a detrimental impact on the health of civilians residing on Vieques. In a study commissioned by Puerto Rican Governor Calderon, a startling 48 out of the 50 Vieques residents tested were diagnosed as suffering from [vibroacoustic disease](/Vibroacoustic_disease), a condition characterized by the thickening of heart tissue, allegedly caused by prolonged exposure to sonic booms. Concurrently, the [Ponce School of Medicine](/Ponce_School_of_Medicine) conducted an independent study that yielded corroborating data, confirming the presence of vibroacoustic disease. Their findings indicated that 79% of Viequense fishermen exhibited thickened heart tissue, the primary symptom of this disease, which can lead to [heart arrhythmia](/Heart_arrhythmia) and, in severe cases, death.

The study conducted by the Ponce School of Medicine underwent a thorough review by the United States [Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry](/Agency_for_Toxic_Substances_and_Disease_Registry) (ATSDR). Tapes of [echocardiograms](/Echocardiogram), which meticulously measured the [pericardial](/Pericardium) thickness, were subjected to blind-coding and forwarded to the Mayo Clinic for independent analysis. This crucial step ensured that the analysts were unaware of whether the study subjects originated from Vieques or a control group. The conclusion reached in 2001 was definitive: "there is no evidence from the Vieques Heart Study to indicate clinically significant heart disease."

### Criticism of Health Risks

The areas designated for the burning of expired ammunition, covering slightly less than 300 acres (1.2 km²), have been acknowledged by the Navy, which has agreed to undertake cleanup operations in accordance with EPA standards. However, in a 2001 press conference, [Robert B. Pirie](/Robert_B._Pirie), the Under Secretary of the Navy, confidently stated: "our training poses no danger and little burden to Viequenses and is absolutely vital to our national security."

Pirie further asserted that the majority of studies linking the Navy's actions to public health declines were conducted by researchers affiliated with the [Puerto Rico Independence Party](/Puerto_Rico_Independence_Party). He maintained that "none of the health-related allegations made have stood-up to credible scientific scrutiny or universally accepted legal standards." Pirie also claimed that the [National Cancer Institute](/National_Cancer_Institute) had reported that cancer rates in many major U.S. cities were, in fact, higher than those observed in Vieques. The institute, however, cautioned that the observed variations in rates could be attributed to chance, given the relatively small population of Vieques. Pirie also contended that figures derived from the Carmen Feliciano data, which suggested an increased infant mortality rate in Vieques, were misleading due to the omission of a range of data in the studies that utilized her information. He argued that when this missing data was factored in, the infant mortality rate was actually lower than that of the rest of Puerto Rico. On behalf of the Navy, Johns Hopkins University School of Hygiene and Public Health conducted a review of the study on vibroacoustic disease conducted by the Vieques government. Their 2001 review found no conclusive evidence to suggest that the symptoms of vibroacoustic disease observed on Vieques were a direct result of noise emanating from Navy exercises. Moreover, Pirie suggested that the report implied that vibroacoustic disease might not, in fact, be a recognized medical condition.

#### ATSDR Study

The [ATSDR](/Agency_for_Toxic_Substances_and_Disease_Registry) undertook extensive testing of water, air, and soil for hazardous materials to ascertain whether the health of the Viequenses was indeed at risk. Their findings concluded that either the Navy's activities had not significantly impacted the environment or the impact was so minimal that the resulting contamination posed no discernible threat to human health. However, a contingent of scientists vehemently disagreed, arguing that the [ATSDR](/ATSDR)'s studies were fundamentally incomplete. The [ATSDR](/ATSDR) has a notorious reputation for denying links between community contamination and adverse health effects. Linda King, from the Environmental Health Network, reported after ten years of monitoring the [ATSDR](/Agency_for_Toxic_Substances_and_Disease_Registry), that only one out of hundreds of ATSDR studies had found contaminants in a community to be the cause of health problems.

In 2003, the [ATSDR](/Agency_for_Toxic_Substances_and_Disease_Registry) issued a determination that it was safe to consume seafood from all waters and coastal lands surrounding the island of Vieques. While acknowledging the detection of several metals in the local seafood, the [ATSDR](/ATSDR) concluded that these metals would not pose a health risk even if an individual consumed fish and shellfish daily for 70 years.

The agency did acknowledge that Navy training had indeed elevated the levels of certain metals in the soil of the former Live Impact Area. However, it maintained that these levels were too low to cause harm to humans. The report concluded that "the public had not been exposed to depleted uranium contamination above normal background (naturally occurring) levels." It further stated that the air did not contain dangerous levels of chemicals, asserting that the Live Impact Area, situated eight miles from residential areas, was too distant for airborne dust and contaminants from training activities to accumulate to concentrations sufficient to cause harm upon contact with civilians. The ATSDR also determined that Naval training and testing had, in no way, affected the island's drinking water supply. Typically, the majority of Vieques's drinking water is supplied via an underwater pipeline from mainland Puerto Rico. The [ATSDR](/ATSDR) report concluded that groundwater from the former Live Impact Area could not contaminate the wells due to the presence of geological barriers. While acknowledging high levels of nitrates in some wells, it attributed this to local sources, most likely agricultural in origin. However, it did caution that it was not safe for children and pregnant women to consume water from these contaminated wells.

#### ATSDR Study Contested

The [ATSDR](/Agency_for_Toxic_Substances_and_Disease_Registry) consistently avoided drawing direct causal links between the Navy's training activities and the health concerns prevalent on Vieques. For instance, the agency conspicuously neglected to test several relevant wells, including the Sun Bay Wells, which serve as a crucial backup water supply for Vieques in the event of a failure in the pipeline from mainland Puerto Rico. Furthermore, the Navy's assertion that groundwater from the testing site could not reach residential groundwater supplies may be factually inaccurate. During a public meeting, when questioned about why the Navy had installed monitoring wells specifically designed to track the spread of explosive contaminants between the impact area and civilian zones, the [ATSDR](/ATSDR) officials refused to provide a comment. The [ATSDR](/ATSDR) also failed to adequately emphasize negative findings within their report, such as the detection of benzene levels exceeding four times the maximum allowed concentration in a groundwater well located on Navy property. By 2009, the [ATSDR](/Agency_for_Toxic_Substances_and_Disease_Registry), facing mounting criticism and a growing body of contradictory evidence, had begun to rescind many of its earlier conclusions.

